title: For Sale:  Fusil Gras MLE 1874 M-80
location: Butts, Henry, Monroe County & Surrounding, Atlanta, Georgia
postcontent:
I have an antique M-80 rifle for sale. This rifle is an antique, and it shows it's age. The rifle belongs to my father in law, who doesn't have access to the internet, so I'm selling for him. He originally received the rifle from his father, and it was passed down throughout time in their family.

A little history about this weapon...The Fusil Gras Modèle 1874 M80 was a French service rifle of the 19th century. This rifle had a caliber of 11 mm and used black powder centerfire cartridges that weighed 25 grams. It was a robust and hard-hitting weapon, but had no magazine and so could only fire one shot after loading. It also had a triangular-shaped sword bayonet, known as the Model 1874 "Gras" Sword Bayonet. The Greek Army adopted the Gras in 1877, and it was used in all conflicts up until the Second World War. 

This particular rifle definitely shows its age. It's missing the ramrod, and I'm pretty sure that the trigger guard has been replaced. The stock is also missing a little "chunk" out of it. The trigger mechanism still works, and the bolt seems to still have a very smooth action, though I've never actually fired the rifle. 

The price is certainly negotiable, so let me know what offers you have. No trades, cash only, and I will meet in the Butts, Monroe, Henry County area...maybe a little further if necessary. The rifle will also come with the softshell case that's pictured.

Thanks!!

title: For Sale:  M1 .30 Carbine Underwood line out Buffalo Barrel WWII
postcontent:
This was my grandfather's rifle when he served in WWII. He passed about 3 years ago and I have only fired the gun twice. It was extremely accurate and fun to shoot, but I just dont have the time to shoot anymore. I have done some research and the gun appears to be very rare, a simillar Underwood line out I saw sold for $1100. The manufacturer listed on the receiver is Underwood with a line through it SN 2758335. The barrel is buffalo (9-1943) but is also stamped with the underwood flaming bomb. It has the flip saftey and the magazine release marked M. It also has the bayonet lug, I used to have the bayonet, but unfortunately lost it during a move. I am also including 4 WWII era magazine hodlers marked from 1943 - 1944 each with 2 magazines from the same time. I have seen the holders with magazines sell from $100 a piece. The gun is in overall good condition for being 70 years old. It does have a few small scrathes in the wood and normal wear showing on the barrel/receiver, but nothing substantial. No cracks. Text me for more pictures/details @ 6147323299 I am asking $1,200 and from the research I have done that appears to be fair and quite possibly a steal. If you feel differently, let me know your offer and why it is fair.

~Lee

title: For Sale:  1841 Remington Contract Percussion Musket
postcontent:
Model 1841 Remington Contract "Mississippi" Rifle - rifling is faint but is the 7-groove rifling. Flayderman Guide grades this gun as Fair condition.

M1841 "Mississippis" saw heavy usage by both Confederates and Union soldiers in the early part of the Civil War--usually by state units--but their popularity declined as more 1861 Springfields were manufactured and issued.

The rear notch sight is intact, and all brass furniture, including barrelbands, triggerguard, sideplate and butt box are intact as is the front sight. Ramrod is of the Civil-War era full-iron replacement variety, as many of the brass-headed ramrods were removed due to metal separation issues in battle. Butt-mounted brass patchbox lid hinge is sturdy, patchbox has a compartment for bullet patches, nipple wrench/screwdriver tool, worm and spare percussion nipple. Brown barrel lacquering (original) is evident in large places along the 33 inch barrel.

Stamped marks on the brass buttstock read "J" over top of a "13". There are two oval cartouches stamped into the wood on the opposite side from the lock to the rear of the brass curled lockplate on that side. To the rear of the hammer on the lock is stamped "US 1849", and in front of the hammer, a very faint "Remington's" with some unintelligible stamping below that.

I believe that the very front of of the stock - muzzle end - of the rifle is a piece of replacement wood, although it looks to be a period replacement - this piece is approximately 11 inches long. Front brass barrel band is slightly loose due to the lack of humidity in Colorado (rifle is originally from Pennsylvania, and was from the Cooper collection out of Baltimore, MD...it was said to be an Antietam battlefield recovery).

Asking $1200 due to condition and piece of replacement wood (I believe) in stock, or best reasonable offer. Face-to-face, cash transactions only. 

Rifle can be seen at my pub (Scruffy Murphy's Irish Pub, 2030 Larimer Street) by appointment only - please email me through Craigslist to set up a time.

postcontent: Customized Ruger 380 LCP - The pistol is has been customized for CCW. One of the issues I had when I acquired the LCP was the low profile sites that were almost non functional for the accuracy that the LCP was capable of delivering so I had the slide dovetailed and fitted for better profile sights including a front tritium night sight. This is something Ruger decided to deliver with the new LC 380 pistol except that the new pistol is significantly heavier, nearly twice the weight. The LCP weights 9oz, one of the lightest .380's made. In addition, the feeding ramp has been highly polished  to increase reliability. The gun has 200-300 rounds through it to break it in for reliability and I have test fired a broad range of ammo without any malfunction. After the break-in and ramp polishing, this been absolutely reliable. The gun is also fitted with a Crimson trace laser and the gun is sighted dead on with both night sights and the CT laser for 15-30 feet combat distance. I have also fitted the gun with a techna clip, belt clip and a home-made trigger block safety of my own making for IWB carry. The trigger block safety I crafted is easy to activate, you just push it out to the left or right as you place your finger on the trigger, yet adds a level of security to enable carrying a round in the chamber. I got the idea for a product I saw for glocks.  I have carried this gun for nearly a year and it disappears; you don't feel it at all in your WB. I have also used a pocket holster and it disappears in your pocket and is included along with a IWB holster. It is incredibly light for a .380; a great summer carry gun. This gun is capable for excellent accuracy for its size, shooting 2-3" groups at 7 yards in fast fire mode for me. The offering comes with the original box, documents, locks, soft case, etc. It also comes with a book hide out I created which holds the gun and two magazines with a dust jacket for a book called 'Forgotten Valor' - see photos. I have for sale or trade a lightly used Ruger LC9. It has only had about 150 rounds shot through it. It has a Galloway Precision trigger job that reduces the trigger pull by half and also has lighter trigger springs form Galloway Precision also that eliminates the stacking at the end of the LC9 trigger pull by reducing the spring power of the firing pin blocker spring and the lifter arm spring. It also has a set of Traction Grips installed on it. They can be removed easily at anytime but I think they help a lot in gripping the gun. I also removed the magazine safety so that the gun will fire with the magazine removed. I still have the stock trigger springs and the magazine safety plate and spring.   I have also polished the whole barrel as the bluing was coming off after shooting the gun. The gun still looks like new with no scratches or blemishes. I have also painted the dots on the sights. The front dot is orange and the rear dots are green. This helps a lot with aiming. It comes with the stock soft case, one magazine with both base plates (flat plate and pinky extension plate), the stock Ruger lock, manuals/ paper work,, box, and the take-down tool.

Description on trigger upgrade from Galloway's site:

The early break trigger system upgrade for the LC9 is the solution for the long heavy false reset of the stock trigger. Our modification to YOUR SUPPLIED hammer and trigger bar will shorten the stroke by half the stock pull length and break at the half way point of the stock travel, all while maintaining the factory safeties. This will allow faster follow up shots and better accuracy due to shorter pull. Expect around a pound reduction in trigger pull weight.

title: For Sale/Trade:  .45cal Kentucky Rifle
postcontent:
I have a CVA .45cal muzzle loader. It's a Kentucky percussion rifle, 36in. Looks and shoots great, has a couple small marks but over all it's in great condition, no rust, good bluing, very nice wood. These guns are super fun to shoot, but I have two and need some room in my safe. I was at Basspro last week and they had everything you need for black powder shooting in stock, balls, caps, wads, powder, everything; it was about  the only thing they did have.

This gun has been inscribed, the side plate reads "Vincere Vel Mori" (05-15-86) Denver Colorado. It means "Conquer or Die". The patch storage brass on the butt stock reads- Serial number 29561 Kentucky Rifle - made for- D.A. Duncan-esg .45cal and has two symbols next to that. It's my guess that someone got this for one of his vet buddies and engraved it for him. It's not professional work but does add some charm to the gun, it looks pretty good and I think it adds something to it. I don't think it helps the value, but I don't think it hurts it either. $150 is a great price for this gun, it's in very good shape.
